xv6 Overview

xv6 is a modern re-implementation of Unix Version 6 (v6), originally created by Dennis Ritchie and Ken Thompson. While xv6 preserves the structure and style of v6, it has been adapted for modern RISC-V multiprocessors and written in ANSI C.

Acknowledgments

The development of xv6 draws inspiration from John Lions's Commentary on UNIX 6th Edition (Peer to Peer Communications; ISBN: 1-57398-013-7; 1st edition, June 14, 2000). Additional resources related to Unix Version 6 can be found at MIT's xv6 page.

Contributions have been made by several individuals, including Russ Cox (context switching, locking), Cliff Frey (multiprocessing), Xiao Yu (multiprocessing), Nickolai Zeldovich, and Austin Clements.

